<p><strong>Ornate Shrew (<em>Sorex ornatus</em>)</strong></p>
<p><strong>Family: </strong>Soricidae<br />
<strong>Genus Species: </strong><em>Sorex ornatus</em><br />
<strong>Common Name: </strong>Ornate Shrew<br /><p>
<p><strong>Identification</strong></p>
<p>The Ornate Shrew is a small mammal with a body size of 2⅓-2½ inches and a tail size of 1½- 1⅘ inches. It is a grayish-brown shrew that is pale beneath, and has 32 teeth. For a more detailed overview of this species see 〔<a href="http://www.enature.com/fieldguides/detail.asp?shapeID=1034&amp;curGroupID=5&amp;lgfromWhere=&amp;curPageNum=9" target="_blank">eNature</a>〕.</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><strong>Habitat Associations and Natural History</strong></p>
<p>Ornate Shrews are found near streams and in wet meadows along the southern two-thirds of Califonia, including Central California. The gestation period is 21 days, occurs at least once a year, and produces a litter of 4-6 newborn. The breeding occurs mainly in the San Francisco Bay Area. These creatures seldom live longer than 12-16 months. The Ornate Shrew is the only shrew to be found over much of its range.<br />
